<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-427-999  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 427 999.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Robotics and Automation  August 1990 v6 n4p445(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Autonomous navigation in a manufacturing environment. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Arkin, Ronald C.; Murphy, Robin R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Flexible manufacturing systems that use automatic guided vehicles(AGVs) are the current choice for manufacturing applications forautonomous mobile robots.andP;  AGVs supply labor savings, efficiency,and less damage to transported materials, but they use a limiteddrivepath and have limited interaction with workstations.andP;  A morecoherent approach to achieving mobility in flexible manufacturingsystems is intelligent navigation.andP;  AuRA is a framework forstudies where intelligent connection of perception to action isdone by mobile robots.andP;  There are five major components to AuRA:the perception, cartographic, planning, motor, and homostaticcontrol systems.andP;  The goal is to have the mobile robot takeadvantage of a priori knowledge of its environment to use a paththat is free of collisions and that does not depend on a fixedtrack or network.andP;  Perceptual strategies using vision andultrasonic sensing should be used to replace the dead reckoning inAGVs.andP;  The workplace should not need to be restructured toaccommodate the navigation needs of a mobile robot.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     RobotsFlexible Manufacturing SystemsNavigationAutomatic Guided VehiclesIEEEComputer Vision.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Schematic diagram of Materials Handling Research CenterLaboratory. (chart)Docking motor schema. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>